{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_1lichtenstein_ver02/data/sn83045462/00280601688/1938012201/0541.xml":{"full_text":"The only evening paper\nin Washington with the\nAssociated Press News\nand Wirephoto Services.\nRfifrll VTT A T? V~ 04 004 Entered at second data matter\nQUU1 X XjAlt. j\\Q. -\u00b1,_o4. D05t otflce, Wathlnaton D. C.\nWASHINGTON, D. C., SATURDAY, JANUARY 22, 1938\u2014THIBTY-TWO PAGES.\nM\u00bb\u00abn. Allocated PrM,. THREE CENTS.\n16 MAJOR OIL COMPANIES\nAND 30 OFFICIALS FOUND\nGUILTY OF PRICE FIXING\nCase Held Largest\nSince Standard\nDissolution.\nYear Imprisonment\nand $5,000 Fine\nIs Maximum,\nBACKGROUND\u2014\nIn largest anti-trust action since\ndissolution of Standard Oil Trust,\n16 major oil companies and 30 of\ntheir officials have been charged\nwith conspiracy to fix Midwestern\ngasoline prices. Taking of testi\nmony and arguments have taken 16\nweeks. Case revolved around pur\nchases of distress gasoline from in\ndependent refineries by major con\ncerns during and after N. R. A.\ncode in 1935 cCTid 1936.\nB> the Associated Press.\nMADISON, Wis., Jan. 22.\u2014A Fed\neral Court jury today convicted 16\nmajor oil companies and 30 of their\nofficials on charges of conspiring to\nraise and fix Midwestern gasoline\nprices during 1935 and 1936 in viola\ntion of the Sherman Anti-Trust Act.\nThe verdict was read before Federal\nJudge Patrick T. Stone and the de\nfendants at 10:29 a,m.\n(Concerning the verdict, Attor\nney General Cummings said here\ntoday:\n\"Naturally I am gratified. It is\na major victory in the enforcement\nof the anti-trust law and my con\ngratulations are extended to Messrs.\nChaffetz, Lewin Crawford and the\nmembers of their staff for the ad\nmirable way in which the Govern\nment case was presented.\u201d)\nThe jury, pondering the voluminous\nevidence that had been introduced dur\ning the 16 weeks of the momentous\ntrial, deliberated about eight hours be\nfore reaching its decision.\nIt received the case yesterday after\nnoon, retired at 11:30 p.m. and was\nready with the verdict shortly after re\nconvening at 8:30 a.m. today.\nLargest Since Standard.\nThe case involved one of the most\nImportant Government anti-trust pro\nceedings in many years. It was the\nbiggest action directed at the petroleum\nindustry since the old Standard Oil\ntrust was dissolved.\nDefendants Will Appeal.\nNearly an hour elapsed from the\ntime the jury was ready to report\nbefore all the defendants could be\nrounded up and summoned to the\ncourtroom.\nWhen the jury came into the court\nroom Judge Stone ascended the bench\nand received the verdict from the\nforeman.\nHe read off the list of the defend\nants\u2014some of the largest oil corpora\ntions in the country, their presidents,\nvice presidents and managers\u2014and\nthen announced all had been found\nguilty as charged.\nThen the judge polled the jury.\nH. H. Thomas of Madison, a de\nfense attorney, immediately informed\nthe court the defendants would file\nmotions for a new trial in the three\ndav period required by law.\nJudge Stone said he would set a\ndate later for arguments on the mo\ntions. When and if they are denied,\nhe will pass sentence.\nThe defendant corporations are\nliable to maximum fines of $5,000\neach. The individuals face similar\nfines or up to a year in prison, or\nboth.\nAlthough Chief Defense Counsel\nWilliam J. Donovan said he had no\nstatement to make, other members\nof the defense staff have said they\nwere ready to carry the case to the\nSupreme Court if necessary.\nOriginal List Larger.\nOriginally 23 oil companies, three\ntrade publications and 46 individuals\nwent on trial, but the number was\nreduced by directed verdicts as the\ntrial progressed.\nThe corporations on trial were:\nSocony-Vacuum Oil Co., Wadhams\nOil Co. (Socony-Vacuum subsidiary).\nStandard Oil Co. of Indiana, Pure Oil\nCo., Sinclair Refining Co., Bamsdall\nRefining Co., Shell Petroleum Corp.,\nIBkelly Oil Co., Continental Oil Co.,\nMid-Continent Petroleum Corp., Cities\nService Co., Empire Oil Refining Co.\n(Cities Service subsidiary), Phillips\nPetroleum Co., Globe Oil Refining\nCo. of Kansas. Globe Oil Refining\nCo. of Illinois, Globe Oil Refining\nCo. of Oklahoma.\nThe individual defendants were:\nEdward G. Seubert, Chicago, presi\ndent, Standard Oil Co. of Indiana.\nAlan Jackson, Chicago, vice presi\ndent in charge of sales, Standard Oil\nCo. of Indiana.\nJacob Prance, Baltimore, president,\nMidcontinent Petroleum Corp.\nI. A. O'Shaughnessy, Minneapolis,\npresident, Globe Oil and Refining Cos.\nA. V. Borque, Tulsa, Okla., secretary,\n(See OIL, Page A-13.)\nDE MULE\u2019S DAUGHTER\nIS PUBLISHER\u2019S BRIDE\nMarried to Joseph W. Harper of\nCalifornia in Ceremony at\nKansas City.\n9 (Picture on Page A-4.)\nI By the Associated Press.\nKANSAS CITY. Jan. 22.\u2014Cecilia\nSe Mille, daughter of Producer and\nMrs. Cecil B. De Mille of Hollywood,\nlast night became the bride of Joseph\nW. Harper, California publisher, in\nthe penthouse of a downtown hotel.\nThe bride was given in marriage by\nher father, here attending the premier\nof- his latest picture.\nMiss Margot Grahame, Hollywood\nactress, was bridesmaid and William\nPine, assistant producer, served as best\nman.\nThe couple will take a wedding trip\nto Europe.\n4\nS--\u2014\nClipper Turns Back 600 Miles\nFrom IJ. S. on Honolulu Flight\nGas Line Trouble Brings Decision to\nTurn About\u2014Passengers, on\nWaking, Think Goal Near.\nBy tfcc Associated Press.\nSAN PEDRO, Calif., Jan. 22.\u2014The\nPan-American Airways China Clipper,\nforced back from a flight to Honolulu\nby gasoline line trouble 600 miles at\nsea. alighted safely in the Los Angeles\nHarbor here at 6:35 a m. (9:35 a.m.\nE. S. T.) today.\nThe giant seaplane's four motors\nwere functioning perfectly as it swung\nin over Long Beach, circled Reeves\nField, naval port on Terminal Island,\nand then settled into the water.\nThe craft was taxied promptly to\nCabrillo Beach, where it dropped an\nchor with a group of naval barges fol\nlowing in its wake.\nSix men passengers boarded one of\nthe Navy boats and were landed. The\ncrew and the two women passengers\ndid not leave the plane immediately.\nThe passengers said that when they\nwere awakened at 5 o'clock this morn\ning and were informed they were going\nto land at San Pedro they thought it\nwas a joke, as they had thought they\nwere nearing Honolulu.\nThey said the steward informed\nthem the gasoline line trouble de\nveloped between an auxiliary tank\nand one of the motors, and although\nthere was no emergency, the crew felt\nit would not have a sufficient fuel\nsupply to make Honolulu without use\nof the gasoline in the spare tank.\nThe passengers said they had not\nbeen informed when the plane would\nresume its trip to Honolulu.\nOne of the crew of a naval barge\nsaid Capt. J, H. Tilton of the plane\nhad told him he had cruised about\nawaiting daylight before landing in\nthe unfamiliar harbor.\nAfter reporting trouble at sea, Capt.\nTilton had been ordered to proceed to\nLos Angeles Harbor since the home\nbase at Alameda, from which the\nClipper took off yesterday, was fog\nbound at the anticipated landing\nhour*.\nPassengers aboard the clipper were\nDonald H. Connolly, W. P. A. admin\nistrator at Los Angeles; Robert Henry\nHinckley, assistant administrator; En\ngel F.lizadle, wealthy Philippine busi\nness man and polo player; Joris Ivens,\nHolland motion picture director; R. S.\nSpringer, official of a Manila drug\ncompany; Melvin Lockett, Los Angeles\naccountant; Mrs. Elizabeth K. Green\nberger, Highland Park, 111; Mrs. Mary\nDorland McCrory, on a Buenos Aires\nto-Manila air tour.\nMODE WAD MONEY\nNEEDED, DIET TOLD\nKonoye Gives Objective as\nChina-Japan-Manchukuo\nEconomic Bloc.\nBACKGROUND\u2014\nJapan has mobilized large num\nbers of reserve troops as well a* the\nregular army and navy for the con\nduct of the war in China. Industry\nalso has been placed under strict\nmobilization for the more effective\ncarrying out of Japan\u2019s aims in\nChina. Finances of Tokio govern\nment in poor shape, with more than\nhalf billion dollars already voted\nfor use of military forces. Stringent\nforeign exchange restrictions im\nposed to support yen exchange.\nB\u00bb the Associated Press.\nTOKIO, Jan. 22.\u2014The Japanese\ngovernment admitted today its need\nfor more money and men to fight\nChina, acknowledged the conflict\nwould be a lengthy one and laid down\nas one of its basic aims an econom\nically linked China, Japan and Man\nchukuo.\nPremier Prince Fumfmaro Konoye\noutlined the economic objectives of\nthe Far Eastern war, and with For\neign Minister Koki Hlrota, Naval Min\nister Admiral Mitsumasa Yonai and\nWar Minister Gen. Gen Sugiyama pre\nsented to the Japanese Diet a de\ntailed account of the six-and-one-half\nmonths of conflict.\nIS _ NG\nEconomists Tell Roosevelt\nOutlook Much Better\nThan Month Ago.\nBACKGROUND\u2014\nRealization shortly before Christ\nmas that business had been in rapid\ndecline since early fall led to series\nof conferences between President\nand spokesmen for ihportant in\ndustrial groups. Talk of co-opera\ntion seemed futile, as administra\ntion blasts were loosed against\nmonopolies and holding companies,\nbut conferences of past two weeks\nhave been surrounded with less of\nantagonistic atmosphere and com\nprehensive programs directed at\nrecovery have been promised by\nseveral participants.\nxueir general conclusions were tnat\nChina\u2019s Generalissimo Chiang Kai\nshek had refused to make peace, there\nfore a new and favorabl China gov\nernment was necessary, that an end to\nthe undeclared war still was \u2019far dis\ntant and that the army must greatly\nincrease its strength in China.\nAnswering questions from the floor\nof Parliament. Konoye said that \u201cif\nnecessary Japan will declare war\nagainst the Chiang Kai-shek regime,\nbut will never deal with it.\u201d\nIncreased Taxes Planned.\nFinance Minister Okinobu Kaya re\nported that, because of the war, it was\nnecessary to raise vast amounts of\nmoney, partly by increased taxes and\nprincipally through bond issues.\nThe regular budget of 2,867,000,000\nyen ($682,760,000) was to be supple\nmented with a special budget for war\nexpenses, Kaya revealed. Anticipating\na rise in commodity prices, he an\nnounced maximums would be fixed,\nand detailed plans for a managed\neconomy.\nThe ministers expressed gratifica\ntion for friendly understanding by\nthe United States' and Britain, per\nmitting peaceful settlement of inci\ndents like sinking of the American\ngunboat Panay, re-emphasized Japan's\nregret for such incidents and renewed\nassurances every effort was being made\nto avoid Injury to third powers.\nIt was for the premier alone, how\never, to deal with the broad and basic\naims for the future.\nWhile Japan was ready to respect\nhe territorial integrity and sovereignty\nof China, and the legitimate rights and\ninterests of third powers there, Prince\nKonoye said, the Japanese govern\nment did hope for a new and co\noperative Chinese regime.\nHe emphasized throughout his ad\ndress a need for the closest economic\nco-operation by China, Japan and her\nprotectorate, Manchukuo, otherwise\nassuming they already constituted a\nsingle Asiatic bloc.\n\u201cFar distant still is an end to the\nconflict,\" the Premier admitted. \u201c1\nshould expect it will be a lqng time\nbefore a settlement is reached.\"\nHe concluded with a national appeal\nfor still greater sacrifices, and praised\ntroops in China.\nHirota for the first time revealed\npeace terms offered through Germany\nto China, and which Chiang Kai-shek\nrefused. This program, he said, was:\n\u201cFirst, China should abandon her\n(See TOKIO, Pate A-13.)\nW'\nBt the Associated Press.\nFederal and private economists alike,\ninformed persons said today, have re\nported to the White House that the\nbusiness outlook has improved sub\nstantially in the last month.\nRecovery has not yet been resumed,\nmost of the economists agreed, but\nthe chart of business health is\nsmoothing out in significant fashion.\nJust when the line will turn up\nward with some assurance of main\ntaining that direction cannot be de\ntermined now, they added.\nJust when the line will turn upward\nwith some assurance of maintaining\nthat direction cannot be determined\nnow, they added.\nOne expert called an important\n\u201cstraw in the wind\" Increased employ\nment in the textile and shoe in\ndustries. The textile increase was\ncontrary to seasonal expectations and\nthe shoe boost was more than sea\nsonal. This expert said these in\ncreases were more important for fore\ncasting than the decreases in many\nother industries.\nNew York Permits Gaty.\nAnother economist attached con\nsiderable significance to a recent jump\nof building permits in New York City.\nA third forecast employment would\nbe higher at the end of this month\n<See BUSINESS, Page A-131\nRUMS REFUSE\nTO LET AMERICAN\nVISIT MRS. RUBENS\nPermission for U. S. Official\nto See Espionage Sus\npect Is Denied.\nSECRETARY WILL STUDY\nCASE OVER WEEK END\nIs Advised Nation Has a Buie\nAgainst Interviewing Prisoners\nDuring Inquiries.\nB? the Associated Press.\nThe Soviet government has refused,\nat least temporarily, the United States\nrequest for an embassy official to see\nMrs. Ruth Marie Rubens, under ar\nrest in Russia on suspicion of es\npionage.\nSecretary of State Hull said he had\nbeen informed by that government\nthat the Soviet internal authorities\ndo not permit the representatives of\nany foreign country to visit persons\nin prison during the course of an\ninvestigation.\nBelieved Inadvisable.\nThe Secretary was advised the for\neign office believed it would be inad\nvisable for embassy officials to visit\nher until after the present Soviet\ninvestigation has been completed.\nThe Soviet government said no ex\nception could be made in the case of\nthe United States.\nSecretary Hull expected to study the\nSoviet report over the week end. There\nis a likelihood that subsequently new\ninstructions will be sent to American\nCharge d'Aflaires Loy Henderson in\nMoscow.\nDetained on Suspicion.\nA few days ago Soviet authorities\ninformed American officials that Mrs.\nRubens had been detained on suspi\ncion of espionage following the arrest\nof a man, presumably her husband,\nwith whom she entered Russia on false\npassports under the name of \u201cMr. and\nMrs. Donald Louis Robinson.\u201d\nThe Soviet statement to Mr. Hender\nson added it had been ascertained\ndefinitely that Mrs. Rubens entered\nRussia in possession of a passport in\nthe name of Ruth Norma Robinson.\nIt was stated, however, that the Soviet\nvisa was valid, by which it was under\nstood that, as Mrs. Robinson, she had\nentered Russia quite openly.\nThis fact was regarded here as a\nmitigating circumstance for Mrs. Ru\nbens. If the visa had been forged as\nwell as the passport falsified, she\nmight have faced serious consequences.\nINDIANA ADVISER BOOMS\nM\u2019NUTT FOR PRESIDENT\nMcHale, Accepting Democratic\nCommittee Post, Praises For\nmer Governor.\nBy the Associated Press.\nFRENCH LICK, Ind., Jan. 22 \u2014In\ndiana was represented on the Demo\ncratic National Committee today by\nFrank McHale. Lotransport attorney,\nwho openly stated a \"Paul V. McNutt\nfor President\u201d boom as he took office.\nMr McHale was elected unanimously\nby the State Comimttee to succeed\nThomas D. Taggart, who resigned after\nserving seven years.\nIn a speech of acceptance Mr. Mc\nHale expressed the hope that \"some\nday we may be able to see some one of\nthe caliber of the leader we have\u2014\nPaul V. McNutt\u2014as Chief Executive\nof the United States.\nMr. McHale, 46 years old, successfully\nmanaged Mr. McNutt's campaign for\nthe office of national commander of\nthe American Legion in 1927 and Gov\nernor of Indiana in 1932. He has been\nconsidered the closest adviser in the\nUnited States to Mr. McNutt, now the\nUnited States high commisisoner to\nthe Philippines.\nBAN STREICHER PAPER\nBERLIN, Jan. 22 (A>).\u2014Publication\nof Germany\u2019s leading anti-Semitic\njournal, Julius Streicher's Der Stuer\nmer, today was banned indefinitely.\nNo reason was disclosed for the ban\nwhich came after this week\u2019s regular\nedition and a special issue had been\nsuppressed.\nSummary of Today's Star\nPage. Page.\nAmusements B-16 Radio _A-9\nChurch News, Real Estate,\nA-10-11-12 B-l to B-5\nComics ..B-14-15 Serial Story...B-5\nEditorials_A-8 Society_A-7\nFinance -A-14 Sports.B-6-7\nLost Found B-9 Woman\u2019s Pg. .B-8\nObituary_A-8\nFOREIGN.\nSoviet refuses to let U. S. official see\nMrs. Rubens. Page a-1\nMore war money and men needed,\nTokio Diet is told. Page A-1\nChautemps opens drive to apply\npolicies. Page A-3\nProtestant English church unity plan\nis advanced. Page A-8\nMexicans assail their government's\ntariff increases. Page A-5\nNATIONAL.\nHouse group favors cut in Oriental\nproduct tax'. Page A-1\nU. 8. Steel to spend $80,000,000 in\n1#3\u00ae- Page A-1\nWhite House told of improved business\noutlook. Page A-1\nChina Clipper limps back 800\nto *\u00bbf\u00abty. Page A-1\nPresident\u2019s naval menage to Congress\ndue Monday. Page A-3\nImportant legislation piling up in\nSenate. Page A-3\nConference report on housing bill goes\nto Senate. Page A-8\nSpeedy trial and execution is planned\nfor Andeea. jags A-1\nWASHINGTON AND VICINITY.\nGovernment seeks collection of $36,000\nfrom Stitely. Page A-*\nBandits get total of $93 and taxicab\nin night's foray. Page A-3\nParley planned on suffrage for District\nof Columbia. Page A-3\n\u201cKind-hearted hopes\u201d futile now, war\nparley told. Page A-6\nIckes defends parfc service personnel\nin address. PageA-13\nOther fish put cod to shame as vita\nmin sources. Page A-16\nBeard and four other prisoners re\nturned to Atlanta. Page A-16\nDeficiency fund of $34,000 sought for\nschool lunch program. Page A-16\nD. C. bill report to include Homeopathic\nHospital purchase. Page A-16\nConstruction of laboratory imperils\nairport project. Page A-16\nEDITORIAL AND COMMENT.\nEditorials. Page A-8\nThis and That. Page A-8\nStars, Men and Atoms. Page A-8\nAnswers to Questions. Page A-8\nThe Capital Parade. Page A-9\nMark Sullivan. Page A-9\nJay Franklin. Page A-9\nLemuel F. Parton. Page A-9\nMISCELLANY.\nShipping News. Page A-9\nVital Statistics. Page A-9\nCity News in Brief. Page A-9\nNature\u2019s Children. PageA-18\nBetsy Caswell. Page B-8\nDorothy Dix. Page B-8\nBedtime Story. Page B-9\nCross-word Pussle. Page B-14\nLetter-Out. Page B-14\nI Contract Bridge. ^PageB-15\nS going!\nMlGHTy FjAST,/1'\ng (WWHEBE4\nJAMES ROOSEVELT SAYS THE EXECUTIVE NEEDS STREAMLINING.\nAndrew t urusetli, Dean of U.\nLabor Movement9 Dies at 83\nANDREW FURUSETH.\nMarch 4, 1915. 19 years later, he\nwalked out of the White House and\nconfronted photographers.\n\u201cYou can take that picture now,\" he\nsaid. The La Toilette Seamen's Act\nhad jusit been signed.\nThroughout his career as union\n(See TURUSEIHT~Page A-13.)\nBody to Lie in State\nin Department\nAuditorium.\ni\nAndrew Furuseth\u2014the \"Old Viking\"\n\u2014dean of the American labor move\nment, died in a nursing home here to\nday at the age of 83.\nHe was president of the Interna\ntional Seamen's Union, and. until old\nage weakened him last year, he had\nattended every convention of the\nAmerican Federation of Labor since\nGrover Cleveland s administration.\nFifty years ago, when he was a\ncrusading Norwegian sailor, Mr. Furu\nseth was elected secretary of the\nSailors\u2019 Union of the Pacific.\nIt was largely through his efforts\nthat the International Seamen's Union\nwas built into a powerful organiza\ntion. Although in poor health, he still\nvisited the Labor Department and\nmembers of Congress in the interest\nof the union's program.\nMr. Furuseth. who is the only Amer\nican labor leader whose bust stands\nin the Labor Department, first came\nto Washington in 1894 to seek pro\ntective legislation for seamen. Pho\ntographers asked permission to take\nhis picture, but he put them off. tell\ning them they could when the legis\nlation he sought was enacted. On\nT. V. A. OPERATION\nIS RULED VALID\nDecision of Federal Court\nSpeeds Case to U. S.\nSupreme Tribunal.\nBACKGROUND\u2014 f\nEighteen private utilities in 1936\nobtained temporary injunction\nagainst T. V. A. operation, claiming\nlaw unconstitutional and charging\ncoercion and conspiracy in effort\nto destroy them. Late yesterday a\nthree-member Federal Court ruled\nevery major activity of Government\nwas valid. The action speeds case\nto the United States Supreme\nCourt, y\nB\u00bb the Associated Press.\nCHATTANOOGA. Tenn., Jan. 22\nThe Tennessee Valley Authority, vic\ntorious over 18 private utilities in a\ntest of its constitutionality, promised\nco-operation today in speeding the\ncase to the United States Supreme\nCourt.\nEvery major activity of the Gov\nernment agency's unified program\n(flood control, navigation and power\nproduction) was held valid yesterday\nby a three-member Federal Court.\nAttorneys for the utilities announced\nthey would appeal. James Lawrence\nFly, T. V. A. chief counsel, said the\nagency would assist \u201cin every way\u201d\ntoward expediting a final decision.\nIn New York, Wall Street reported\nthat utility security owners were de\npressed, especially by the ruling that\nT. V. A. power competition was not\nonly \"lawful\u201d but that privately owned\npower companies \u201chave* no immunity\nfrom lawful competition even if their\nbusiness be curtailed or destroyed.\u201d\nHowever, the financial community\nbelieved generally that power securi\nties already had discounted the pos\nsibility of a pro-T. V. A. decision, hav\ning been weak for some time.\nHailed by LMenthal.\n\u201cThe decision paves the way for a\nrational, businesslike adjustment of\nrelations between T. V. A. and the\nprivate power companies,\u201d said David\nE. Lillenthal, the T. V. A. director,\nwho was most concerned since the\nelectric program was inaugurated un\nder his guidance.\n\u201cT. V. A. can go forward in the de\nvelopment and saving, of our national\nresources without the lawsuits which\nhave held up this constructive work\nfor four years.\u201d\nThe reaction in Washington was\nvaried.\n\u201cIn view of the fact Sister Allen was\na member of the court, I am not sur\nprised,\u201d said Representative Knutson,\nMinnesota Republican and T. V. A.\ncritic, citing the presence on the tri\nbunal of Circuit Judge Florence Allen\nof Ohio, an appointee of President\nRoosevelt.\nMississippi\u2019s Democratic Represent\native, Rankin, a T. V. A. champion,\nsaid, \u201cI hope it will mean the end of\nthe attempt of the power trust to con\n(See t. v. a* Paayt-i3.)\nMAH PRODUCTS\nTAX IMPOSED\nHouse Group Favors Slash\nin Excise Levy'on\nOilseeds.\nBy CONSTANTINE BROWN.\nThe recomendations of the sub\ncommittee of the House Ways and\nMeans Committee to slash the excise\ntax on certain \"Oriental products\"\u2014\nmainly from Manchukuo\u2014has caused\na mild sensation in Washington diplo\nmatic quarters.\nAt a time when many individuals\nare advocating a boycott of Japanese\ngoods as the best means to force\nJapan to cease her aggression in\nChina, the House committee recom\nmends the following reduction from\na uniform \"2-cents-a-pound levy:\nHempseed, to 1.12; perilla, to 1.31;\nrapeseed. to 1.51; kapock, to 0.73, and\nsesame, to 1.05.\nTax Put on in 1934.\nThese products were coming Into\nthe United States without charge un\ntil 1934 when an excise tax of 2 cents\nper pound was established.\nThis recommendation shows the\nlack of cohesion between the foreign\npolicy of the administration and the\ntax policy of the Congress. While\nthe State Department is endeavoring\nto establish close economis ties with\nthe South American republics the\nCongress favors goods from a coun\ntry with which we have strained re\nlations to the detriment of our friends\nh the South.\nArgentine at the present moment is\ncoasidering a trade agreement with\nthe United States. One of the\nprincipal exports of that country to\nAmerica is flax seed. The Oriental\nseeds are competing with this chief\nexport of Argentina.\nThe tariff on flaxseed is at the\npresent moment 65 cents per bushel\nor a little over 2% cents per pound.\nArgentines Fear Export Cat.\nThe Argentine exporters were able\nto compete with the Manchukuoan\nseeds as long as the 2-cent excise tax\nwas enforced. But they believe that\nthe new tax, if passed by the Con\ngress, will drastically curtail the Ar\ngentine flaxseed. All these oil seeds\nare used in the paint and varnish in\ndustry.\nHow important this matter is for\nArgentina can be seen from the fact\nthat in the fiscal year 1936-1937 we\nimported 26,000,000 bushels of flax\nseed from that South American re\npublic. In the first five months of the\n1937-38 fiscal year the imports\namounted to 9,000,000 bushels. A re\nduction of import duties, as recom\nmended by the Vinson subcommittee,\nis believed to affect seriously the trade\nrelations with Argentina.\nTwo Quake* in Montana.\nHELENA, Mont., Jan. 22 (A1).\u2014Two\n\u201cweak\u201d earthquakes were felt here\nyesterday. Bach lasted about one sec\nond.\nHUNT FOR LEADER\nCoast Authorities Continue\nQuiz of Suspect, Begin\nSearch for Store.\n<Picture on Page A-2.)\nBv the Associated Press.\nSEATTLE, Jan. 22.\u2014Police author\nities looked for a \"plot behind the\nplot\" today in their investigation of a\nbizarre attempt to bomb the Japanese\nliner Hiye Maru.\nInvestigators said the death of\nRolphe M. Forsyth. 28. Vancouver,\nB. C school teacher who drowned\nThursday after pushing a bomb-laden\nraft toward the liner, might have\nsealed the secret of the fantastic plot.\nBut they continued to question George\nHenry Partridge, 22, also of Vancouver,\nForsyth's admitted accomplice.\n\"Experience with espionage will con\nvince you,\u201d Police Capt. Marshall\nScrafTord said, \"that attempts of this\nkind always are carried on by isolated\nI units, ostensibly, entirely divorced from\ni any guiding hand behind the scenes.\nBelieves Others Involved.\n\"But by experience and that of all\nmy colleagues in this case also leads\nus to believe there must be some per\nson or agency directing the activities\nof this bombing unit.\u201d\nAt Vancouver, where the Hive Maru\nwas due to dock today under special\nguard. Chinese Consul General C. H.\nPao said he had \"absolutely no knowl\nedge\" of the purported plot. At San\nFrancisco, Chinese Consul General\nC. C. Huang likewise denied any\nknowledge of a proposal to bomb ships\ncarrying scrap metal to Japan.\nPolice said the home-made bomb,\ncontaining enough dynamite to blow\na 6-foot hole in the hull of the liner,\nmissed Are only because water leaking\ninto the bomb's covering, a suitcase,\nstopped the time device when the con\ntact hand was only one-eighth of an\ninch from the firing position.\nSeek Place of Sale.\nPolice Lts. W. J. O'Brien and F. A.\nHimes, who helped take the 369 dyna\nmite sticks from the bomb, found in\nthe water where Forsyth apparently\ndrowned pushing it toward the Hiye\nMaru, turned to Tacoma, Wash., in a\nsearch for the place where the ex\nplosive was obtained. They said its\nwrapping came from a Tacoma hard\nware store, but explained any one\ncould buy dynamite from commercial\noutlets without a permit.\nCustoms Inspector P. W. Copestick\nsaid Forsyth, who swam a great dis\ntance in cold water, could have walked\nto within 15 or 20 feet of the Hiye\nMaru had he known the water front.\nMr. Partridge said a policeman un\nknowingly aided them by directing\nhim and Forsyth to the water front\nwith their \"infernal machine.\u201d\nJAPANESE SILENT\nON WARSHIP PLANS\nNavy Office Spokesman Declines\nto Confirm Battleships Over\n35,000 Tons.\nB> the Associated Press.\nTOKIO, Jan. 22.\u2014One Japanese\nnaval office spokesman declined today\nto say whether Japan secretly was\nbuilding battleships of more than\n35,000 tons, although Domei (Japanese\nnews agency) reported a naval office\ndenial from a seeond official.\nQuestions after the British govern\nment instructed its Ambassador to\nTokio to pursue reports Japan was\nbuilding or planning 43.000-ton battle\nships, with 18-inch guns. Rear Admiral\nKiyoshi Noda told newspaper men.\n\u201cI am unable to take the responsi\nbility of affirming or denying. If\ndenied, the next question may be\n\u201842,000 tons,\u2019 etc.\u201d\nSuch construction would be above\n1936 London naval treaty limitations\nto 35,000-ton capital ships and 16-inch\nguns.\nAdmiral Noda\u2019s office said the\nDomei denial was from another offi\ncial, who presumably had authority to\nspeak for the naval office.\nEnvoy Flies to 111 Father.\nMIAMI, Fla., Jan. 22 OP).\u2014Dr. Don\nLeon De Bayle, Nicaraguan Minister\nto Washington, made a reservation on\nthe Pan-American Clipper leaving for\nCristobal, Canal Zone, this morning\nto fly to the bedside of his father,\nwho is seriously ill In Managua,\nNicaragua,\nII. S. STEEL PLANS\nMO,000 OUTLAY\nTO BETTED PLANTS\nFairless Tells Senate Un\nemployment Unit Half to\nBe Spent by April 1.\nCOMPLETES $253,000,000\nPROGRAM BEGUN IN 1933\nInstitute Head Says Industry Has\nExpended $650,000,000 for Cap\nital Goods in Three Years.\nBACKGROUND\u2014\nSenate voted $10,000 last sum\nmer for study of unemployment and\ncommittee directed a formulation\nof long-time national program of\nhandling relief. Sudden appearance\nof business decline and sharp in\ncrease in unemployment led com\nmittee to turn its attention to\nimmediate situation. Leaders of\nGovernment, industry and labor\nhave appeared during three weeks\nof hearinzgs.\nBy JOHN C. HENRY.\nBenjamin F. Fairless, president of\nthe United States Steel Corp., in\nformed the Senate Unemployment\nCommittee today that his company\nplans expenditure of at least $80,000.\n000 on plant modernization during\n1938.\nOf this sum. Mr. Fairless stated in\na letter read to the committee, about\n$40,000,000 will be expended before\nApril 1, with the remainder being used\nduring the second and third quarters\nof the year.\n\u201cIn addition.\u201d Mr. Fairless\u2019 letter\nsaid, \u201cif business conditions warrant,\nthere will be. undoubtedly, other ex\npenditures in considerable amounts\nduring 1938.\"\nTo Complete Huge Program.\nMr. Fairless, prevented by illness\nfrom appearing in person, wrote that\nthe contemplated expenditures would\ncomplete a S253,000,000 program au\nthorized in 1933.\nFor the industry as a whole, Walter\nS. Tower, executive secretary of the\nAmerican Iron and Steel Institute, tes\ntified that:\n\u201cIn the three years 1935-1937, ap\nproximately $650,000,000 was spent by\ncompanies in the iron and steel in\ndustry for new plants and equipment.\nOf the total amount spent by the in\ndustry for new equipment and con\nstruction during the past three years,\n$290,000,000 was spent in 1937; about\n$216,000,000 in 1936 and $140,000,000\nin 1935.\"\nRemarking on the dependence of\nsteel upon industries which buy from\nit. Mr. Fairless indorsed efforts\nto stimulate the durable goods in\ndustries and housing construction. By\nimplication, also, he approved current\nefforts of the railroads to obtain added\nrevenue by increasing rates.\n\u201cThe railroads have been out of\nthe steel market for a long period.\u201d\nthe steel executive wrote. \u201cTheir\nproperties need in maintenance large\nsupplies of steel products. Without\nmoney, the railroads cannot buy. They\nmust find the financial means to meet\ntheir current maintenance expenses.\nHousing Program Benefits.\n\u201cAlthough there will be little direct\nbenefit to the steel industry in an en\nlarged and proper housing program,\nthe benefit in the broad economic sense\nto industry as a whole should be great.\u201d\n\u201cThere is some indication of some\npresent improvement,\u201d he added,\n\"principally, as I view it now, in the\nreplenishing of stocks of material re\nquired by reason of the dimunition of\ninventory stocks\u2014a buying for imme\ndiate necessities.\u201d\nTouching on the question of price\nstructure, Mr. Fairless informed the\ncommittee there are many views that\nhave been expressed.\n\u201cIt is clear that prices cannot be\nreduced without a corresponding re\nduction in costs, of which wages is\nthe most important part.\u201d\nMr. Fairless' company is operating\nunder a wage contract with the Steel\nWorkers\u2019 Organizing Committee, an\naffiliate of the Committee for Indus\ntrial Organization. The present con\ntract expires at the end of February.\nMr. Faidless wrote that export trade\nin steel is holding up, but specified\nthat \u201cThere is no indication of any\nrelation between the subsidiary com\npanies\u2019 export business and armament\npreparations in European countries\nanrt .Tannn\nSlight Pick-up in Operation.\nMr. Tower testified that there has\nbeen a slight pick-up in steel opera\ntions in January from below 20 per\ncent to 29.8 per cent of capacity.\n\"Indications are for at least a mod\nerate measure of further improvement\nduring the early months of the year,\"\nhe said.\nSteel wages and employment were\nat a record high in 1937, Mr. Tower\nsaid under questioning, he admitted\nthat a 31 per cent increase in labor\ncosts alone would not justify the price\nincrease of 21 per cent in steel pro\nduced.\nMr. Tower conceded the merit of a\nprogram of Government construction\nplanned to coincide with declines in\nprivate work, but would not agree\nthat the steel industry might likewise\nintegrate its modernization plana to\nspend most in slack times.\n\u201cI would think that executivea\nwould hesitate to sit around and\nplan as you suggest,\u201d he said, \"for\nfear they might be charged with\nagreeing on other things.\u201d\n\"Very timid about violating the\nanti-trust laws, aren\u2019t they?\u201d Senator\nMurray, Democrat, of Montana ob\nserved.\nAlarm Called \u201cHysterical.\u201d\nDescribing as \u201chysterical\u201d the alarm\nwhich greeted the \u201cmild recession of\nprivate construction activity,\u201d Thomas\nS. Holden, vice president of the P.\nW. Dodge Corp., said it was merely\nthe dissipation of \"false expectations\nof a speculative housing boom.\u201d\nMr. Holden discounted estimates of\ngreat housing needs, saying that short\nage exists only for those of low In\n(See UNEMPLOYMENT, Page A-13.)","height":"31228","width":"22300"}}
